<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Ceanothus megacarpus </i>is an evergreen shrub that grows to 4 m in height. It is a shallow-rooted species and has an extremely high tolerance for xylem moisture stress, similar to desert shrubs such as <i>Larrea tridentata </i>(Kolb and Davis 1994). Shrubs begin producing seed at 5 years. When capsules dry, they explosively cast seeds away from the parent plant, but most seeds drop beneath is crown. Seed predation by small mammals and insects may be high, but seeds eventually collect in the duff and soil, forming a persistent seed bank (Montygierd-Loyba and Keeley 1987). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Ceanothus megacarpus </i>is endemic to the western Transverse Ranges and Channel Islands, and the center of its distribution is in the Santa Monica Mountains. It commonly occurs as dense stands from low to moderate elevations on variable aspects throughout the region. The <i>Ceanothus megacarpus </i>alliance appears to have become more abundant in the Santa Monica Mountains over the past 60-70 years, while <i>Adenostoma fasciculatum </i>has declined (R. Taylor pers. comm. 2004). The alliance also occurs further north into the Santa Ynez and San Rafael mountains in dense stands on gentle to steep, south- to west-facing slopes (Keeley 2007). We include the two <i>C. megacarpus </i>varieties (Fross and Wilken 2006, Hickman 1993) in the alliance; var. <i>megacarpus </i>occurs on the mainland, and var. <i>insularis </i>(a CNPS List 4.3 plant) on the Channel Islands. We also include in this alliance stands that have <i>C. megacarpus </i>co-dominant with <i>A. fasciculatum, </i>or <i>C. megacarpus </i>dominant with other chaparral species subdominant </div>
</div>

    
	
	
