    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Bb-c, Be-h). Stands are described for the Santa Ynez Mountains (Borchert et al. 2004), Santa Monica Mountains (Keeler-Wolf and Evens 2006), and the section in general (Keeley 2007). Plants of var. insularis form stands on Santa Catalina and San Clemente islands (Junak et al. 2007, Landis 1997).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Ba, Bd). Stands exist in the San Rafael and Topatopa mountains (Borchert et al. 1993b) Records of this species in the past in the San Gabriel Mountains (UCB 2006) may have been extirpated by recent fires.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Repeated short-interval fires of < 25 years deplete the seed bank. <i>Ceanothus megacarpus </i>is well suited for use in restoration because of its rapid growth rate and an ability to improve soil fertility through fixing nitrogen. </div>
</div>

    

    

